```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

struct UserData {
    uint32_t user_id;
    std::string name;

    void serialise(auto& stream) {
        stream << user_id << name;
    }
};

void serialize_object(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, const UserData& data) {
    // Call the object's serialise method with the writer stream
    const_cast<UserData&>(data).serialise(writer);
}

void deserialize_object(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader, UserData& data) {
    // Call the object's serialise method with the reader stream
    // The serialise method works for both serialization and deserialization
    data.serialise(reader);
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. **`serialize_object`**: This function takes a `binary_stream_writer` and serializes the `UserData` object by calling its `serialise()` method. Since the parameter is `const UserData&` but the `serialise()` method is non-const, we use `const_cast` to remove the const qualifier. When called with a writer, the `<<` operators in the `serialise()` method will write the data to the stream.

2. **`deserialize_object`**: This function takes a `binary_stream_reader` and deserializes into the `UserData` object by calling its `serialise()` method. The same `serialise()` method works for deserialization because the Hexi library's stream adaptors can handle both reading and writing operations through the same interface (the `<<` operator adapts based on the stream type).

This approach leverages the fact that the Hexi library supports using the same `serialise()` method for both serialization and deserialization through template-based stream adaptors.

