    PoolObject* obj3 = allocator.allocate();
    *obj3 = PoolObject(3, 30.9);
    pool.push_back(obj3);

    return pool;
}
```

I'll allocate three objects from the pool, assign each one a distinct pair of values by constructing temporary `PoolObject` instances and copying them into the allocated memory, then collect all the pointers in a vector before returning it.

Alternatively, if the allocator provides raw memory without construction, I could use placement new to initialize objects directly at their allocated addresses:

```cpp
std::vector<PoolObject*> create_object_pool(hexi::block_allocator<PoolObject, 10>& allocator) {
    std::vector<PoolObject*> pool;

    // Allocate and initialize 3 objects
    PoolObject* obj1 = allocator.allocate();
