}
```

This placement new approach constructs each object in-place at the allocated memory address, which is more efficient than assignment if the allocator doesn't already call constructors.

However, the comment about requiring a default constructor suggests the allocator likely handles construction itself, so the simpler assignment approach would be more appropriate. I can streamline this by assigning constructed temporary objects to each allocated pointer rather than repeating the allocate-and-push pattern multiple times.

